[{"id":"VR797891","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two steps in an experiment involving two spheres, labeled Sphere 1 and Sphere 2, on separate stands. In the first step, each sphere is connected to ground through a wire held in contact with the sphere by a student and a positive rod is next to each sphere. In the second step, the wire in contact with Sphere 1 is removed while the other wire remains in contact with Sphere 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR797891.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two identical, electrically neutral conducting spheres, Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, are on insulating stands. Each sphere is connected to ground through a wire held in contact with the sphere by a student, as shown in the figure. A positively charged insulating rod is then brought close to each sphere. With the rods close to the spheres, the wire in contact with Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is removed while the other wire remains in contact with Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. The rods are moved far away from the spheres, after which the wire in contact with Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is removed as well. Which of the following correctly describes the final net charge, if any, on the two spheres?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR797891_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both spheres have a negative net charge.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both spheres are electrically neutral.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> has a negative net charge and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is electrically neutral.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is electrically neutral and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> has a negative net charge.</p>"],"answer":2}]